snippet.textDisplay:
Cynics: 'Apple has created a revolutionary product that is innovative, makes life easier, pushes the world a step closer towards a truly wireless future and has been shamelessly ripped off by the whole industry.'

Also cynics: 'Apple creates problems and then sells solutions to those problems to get dat money' 

The game is rigged against Apple. Damned if you innovate, damned if you don't. Yes, Apple charges a bit too much for its products.. Duh! That's no secret. But, when the rest of the industry inevitably replicates its products, everyone stands to benefit from the trickle-down effect of that innovation. And thus, technology that would otherwise have taken years to reach the average user reaches them a lot faster, and thus, takes the whole world one step closer to the future of tech.

If Apple took the cynics and the 'rational' critics of 20 years ago seriously, we'd still be using some version of the floppy disk and other long outmoded tech in the name of nostalgia and / or misplaced rationalism.

snippet.textDisplay: Wrong to say that removing the headphone jack created a problem... Most people use the wired earbuds that come with the iPhone... when Apple removed the old round jack, they simply put the lightning connector on the Apple Earbuds... so, like before... most people buying iPhones continued to use the included wired earbuds. Those who rather use bluetooth are going to do that wether or not there's an old round jack available. So I think you got it backwards, Apple did not have to make bluetooth earbuds because there was no jack (and BT buds were already on market), but rather, Apple was able to remove the old jack which prevented waterproofness, took up too much space) add lightning to earbuds for those that use those, then added the AirPods to the market because that was the direction bluetooth earbuds were going anyway.  What's new about AirPods isn't that they are wireless (that's been out for years and used by millions), what's new is there was no wire between the two buds (also already out for a year or two?) which is irrelevant to the headphone jack.  The purpose of the adapter is for people who want to use their old wired earbuds they bought from Shure or somebody or full size over ear headphones.

snippet.textDisplay:
Really? Other companies are copying the Airpods so they can sell a work-alike - and get a big chunk of that money - without the exorbitant Apple mark-up. The Android phones getting rid of their headphone jacks isn't so much because that's a better idea for "the future" but rather because it allows them to cut costs (and that punishing weight) by eliminating the headphone jack. Samsung tried to to the same type of thing with the Galaxy S6 when they tried to eliminate a handful of software and hardware features that the Android gearheads liked in an attempt to push the phone market in a direction that worked better for them than for their customers. (They brought most of those features back with the Galaxy S7.)



Luckily, I have a late model Android phone that still has the headphone jack. So I can charge my phone, rock out with (much less expensive) knck-off BT earbuds that deliver great sound and long play times or uae one of my wired ear buds to get the best sound.
